PARNELL PICKED FOR USDA POST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
California farm chief Jack Parnell was nominated by President Bush to be deputy 
U.S. secretary of agriculture. Parnell, 53, director of the state Department of 
Food and Agriculture since 1987, is the first Californian chosen for a 
high-level job in the Bush Administration. If confirmed by the Senate, he will 
be chief deputy to Agriculture Secretary Clayton K. Yeutter. Republican 
Parnell, who has a 4,000-acre ranch near Auburn, is a former auctioneer of 
pedigree livestock and agricultural magazine editor. 
