ORANGE COUNTY DIGEST: LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
MIDWAY CITY; 
</P>
<P>
SUPERVISOR STANTON LENDS HIS NAME TO PARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Board of Supervisors agreed to name a new 1.4-acre park in unincorporated 
Midway City after Supervisor Roger R. Stanton. 
</P>
<P>
The park, located in Stanton's 1st District, was built in 1987 on land acquired 
by the county from Southern California Edison, Co. The recommendation to name 
the park in Stanton's honor came from the Midway City Chamber of Commerce and 
Homeowner's Assn. The park -- bounded by Bolsa Avenue and Riata, Purdy and 
Washington streets -- includes a 4,000-square-foot community center where 
programs involving hot meals for senior citizens and day care for young 
children are operated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
HONORS; PARKS -- ORANGE COUNTY; STANTON, ROGER R 
</P>
