<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEALTH FILE: SMELLING TROUBLE AFTER RADIATION TREATMENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: The husband of a friend of mine had radiation treatments, and now my 
friend says that things don't smell the same to him any more. Could this have 
been caused by the treatments, or is it just a coincidence? Does this usually 
happen in such cases? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: The use of radiation in cancers of the head and neck has been reported 
to affect the sense of smell. Many patients experience some improvement a few 
months after treatment, but some residual impairment is often the rule. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Two of my friends have had to have hysterectomies, and their reactions to it 
have been as different as night and day. One of them is acting as if the world 
has come to an end, while the other one has told me that she looks on it as if 
she had to have a tooth extracted. How can you account for this difference in 
attitude? 
</P>
<P>
A: A number of factors may help determine a woman's reaction to the need for a 
hysterectomy. For example, a 25-year-old childless woman may be more concerned 
about having a hysterectomy than a 55-year-old mother. The reason for the 
procedure and any complications associated with it may also influence the 
woman's attitude and reaction. 
</P>
<P>
Cultural factors also appear to play a role. The results of various studies 
have shown that women from different cultural and ethnic backgrounds show 
different degrees of anxiety and depression both before and after surgery. In 
addition, women who were better educated appeared to tolerate the procedure 
better than did less well educated women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
